            <h4>18. Runs and charges setup</h4>
            <hr />
            <p>
                Summary: in this step the boarding charges and basic information for runs is configured. <br />
                *     Who can skip this step? Nobody. Businesses that do not offer overnight boarding services still need­ to configure basic information about runs and other charges. <br />
                *     How to get here: ‘Options,’ ‘Settings,’ and ‘Charges.’ <br />
                <br />
                <strong>Runs and charges</strong> <br />
                Summary: in this step you determine the general boarding pricing structure of your business. <br />
                *     Who can skip this step? Nobody.<br />
                <br />
                1.      In the area for ‘General Charges’ choose either default to ‘Charge by Run Type’ or ‘Charge by Pet Size’ depending on your business model.
                        When charging by ‘run type’ the size of the pet will not have any effect on the boarding charges. On the other hand, when charging by ‘pet size’
                        runs can be configured to ‘override’ the pet size’s rate. ‘Overriding’ rates is necessary when you have specific run types (e.g. suites) that can
                        have a fixed rate regardless of pets that are in them. <br />
                <img ng-src="{{'img_help/help.18.2.png' | baseUrl}}" alt="" />
                <br />
                *     Regardless of your standard charge policy (runs or sizes), both pet’s sizes and runs need to be set up. All pets are defined to be of a given
                    size (this information is used for analysis of pets and visits in reports). For example, Fluffy can be a ‘Small’ or ‘Large’ animal, regardless of the run Fluffy might be staying in.<br />
                <br />
                2.      In the area for ‘Pet Size and Rates Set Up’ enter all desired names for your pet sizes.<br />
                <br />
                *     There are 12 available pet sizes, if you don’t wish to use one of them don’t clear any fields just set the ‘In Use’ column to unchecked. You can’t add or delete ‘Pet Sizes.’<br />
                *     If you don’t wish to worry about recording the pet’s sizes, just create a single size and call it ‘Regular.’ At least one pet size will be needed for the system to work properly.<br />
                <br />
                <img ng-src="{{'img_help/help.18.1.png' | baseUrl}}" alt="" />
                <br /><br />
                3.      If you charge by the pet size, enter the ‘Rate’ and the ‘Half Day Rate’ for all sizes with ‘In Use’ set to checked, The ‘Rate’ represents the daily rate if the pet checks out after
                    the ‘Check Out Time’ (just like in a hotel). The ‘Check Out Time’ will be configured later. If you don’t charge anything if checking out before the ‘Check Out Time’ set the ‘Half Day Rate’ to zero. <br />
                4.      If you charge by the run type you can skip to the next step. In the area for ‘Run Types and Rates Set Up’ make sure all columns for ‘Override’ are set to unchecked, unless you want that run
                        type’s rate to override the pet size’s rate. For example. Let’s say Fluffy is of size ‘Regular’ and the ‘Rate’ for that size is 14. If all runs are set to unchecked for ‘Override,’ Fluffy
                        will be charge a daily fee of 14 regardless of the run he is in. However, if a run let’s say ‘Suite’ is set to ‘Y’ ‘Override’ with a rate of 20, then Fluffy will be charged 20 per day instead of the 14. <br />
                5.      In the area for ‘Run Types and Rates Set Up’ enter all desired names for your run types.. Even if you charge by the pet size, you still need to configure what types of runs you have available. <br />
                <br />
                *     The first run type called ‘No Charge’ is required by the system and can’t be modified in any way.<br />
                *     You can’t delete run types. If you don’t want to use a given run type just set the ‘In Use’ value to unchecked Do not leave any values blank..<br />
                <br />
                6.      Make sure all desired run types have ‘In Use’ set to checked and a limit greater than 0. The ‘Limit’ is used to calculate vacancies.
                        Is important to have very accurate limits for each one of your runs. <br />
                <br />
                *     If you only have one type of run, you can have one single run type called ‘Regular.’<br />
                <br />
                <img ng-src="{{'img_help/help.18.3.png' | baseUrl}}" alt="" />
                <br /><br />
                <h4>Example of boarding charges</h4>
                <br />
                <p>
                    Boarding Charges (Not Using Half Day Rates) <br />
                    <br />
                    The following example illustrates how boarding charges apply. This example assumes half day boarding is not being used. Charges for a pet that checks in 9/1 leaves 9/7 will be: <br />
                    <br />
                    *     if check in time (e.g. 11:30 AM on 9/1) is AFTER check out time (e.g. 11:25 AM on 9/7) <br />
                    o   Charges: 6 full boarding days <br />
                    *     if check in time (e.g. 10:00 AM on 9/1) is BEFORE check out time (e.g. 11:25 AM on 9/7) <br />
                    o   Charges: 7 full boarding days <br />
                    <br />
                    Check Out time: The check out time can be configured 'Boarding settings' as either rigid (e.g. 1:00 PM) <br />
                    or flexible based on the check in time per pet plus a given number of hours <br />
                    <br />
                    <img ng-src="{{'img_help/help.18.4.png' | baseUrl}}" alt="" />
                    <br />
                </p>
                <br />
                <strong>Boarding commissions setup</strong> <br />
                <br />
                <p>
                    Summary: in this step new client commissions will be configured. <br />
                    *     Who can skip this step? Businesses that do not pay new client boarding commissions. <br />
                    *     How to get here? Go to ‘Options’ ‘Settings,’ ‘Commissions,’ <br />
                    <br />
                    1.      This is where you can select if an employee will receive a commission for signing up a new client who boards. Simply set an amount and it will credit that employee with the commission. <br />
                    2.      If you are not using this feature set the amount to 0.<br />
                    <br />
                    *     Whoever enters the new client will be the person receiving the commission.<br />
                    <br />
                    *     To search for commissions open up reports, click all reports, check commissions under the boarding section and hit Open Reports.<br />
                    <img ng-src="{{'img_help/help.18.5.png' | baseUrl}}" alt="" />
                    <br />
                </p>
                <strong>Boarding discounts setup</strong> <br />
                <br />
                <p>
                    Summary: in this step boarding discounts are configured, including long term boarding, total bill discount (e.g. military, senior citizen), first time client, and multiple pets boarding together. <br />
                    *     Who can skip this step? Businesses that do not offer boarding discounts.<br />
                    *     How to get here: ‘Set Up,’ ‘Settings,’ and ‘Discounts,' and 'Boarding.'<br />
                    <br />
                    1. Check this if you wish to set up long term discounts. <br />
                    2. If you check the option a separate section will show up underneath.<br />
                    3. The long term discount refers to pets boarding over a given number of days. If a pet qualifies for the ‘2nd Long Term’ discount it will not be given a
                       ‘Long Term’ (1st term) discount. For example, let’s say the daily rate for Fluffy is 10 with a long term of 10% after 5 days, and 20% of after 15 days.
